    "body": "### Problem\n\nJulialang, THE math/science language,\r\nhas *all sorts of characters that can be entered,\r\nhttps://docs.julialang.org/en/v1/manual/unicode-input/\r\n\r\n& given that it's a math/engineering/science language,\r\nit's important that these be the same in one's editor as they are in the language\r\n\r\n( having to learn 2 entire sets of entry-\"shortcuts\",\r\ne.g. :digraphs in Vim & Neovim,\r\nthen Julia's \\Gamma for the angular Greek capital-G,\r\nis a *insane* abuse-of-finite-mental-resources from our entire population. )\r\n\r\nNeovim NEEDS to give us the ability to have our entry-method MATCH Julialang's items.\r\n\r\nWHEN I enter\r\n\r\n:iab \\copyright <ctrl-v>u00a9\r\n\r\n( I'm using this as an example, simply because the Greek characters are less likely to be installed on a system than the copyright-symbol is,\r\nbut it's the same error, for the entire Greek alphabet )\r\n\r\nboth Vim & Neovim 9.5 give the error\r\n\r\nE474: Invalid argument\r\n\r\n\"Oh, but you HAVE TO USE VIM'S DIGRAPHS,\r\n& then when you're in Julia, you have to use their shortcuts, instead:\r\nMEMORIZE BOTH, to be able to work,\r\nXOR go switch to some other editor-type!\"\r\n\r\n*isn't* The Right Answer(tm),\r\nif you see what I mean..\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nIt doesn't work when one is in the editor, AND it doesn't work in .vimrc.\r\n\r\nIn my .vimrc I've got these, to try to make it work,\r\n& it still doesn't work:\r\n\r\nset encoding=utf-8\r\nset fileencoding=utf-8\r\nscriptencoding utf-8\r\n\r\n( notice the different-format of that one, which took much bashing around the 'web to discover, as almost-all of the \"help\" out there got that wrong, some including an equals-sign, some including \"set \", etc..\r\nagain, needless arbitrary-memorization is required, abusing finite mental-resources.. )\r\n\r\nthen..\r\n\r\niab  \\copyright  <ctrl-v>u00a9 ( this produces the actual-symbol that I want to appear, when I type-in \\copyright )\r\n\r\nis broken.\r\n\r\n\r\nI'm asking that Neovim be caused to accept the COMPLETE set of Unicode as input-abbreviations:\r\n\r\nThis would allow people with their *names* in other-character-sets to use :iab to get their *actual* name in their English text-documents,\r\nand this would fix Julia-users' working with Neovim, simultaneously.\r\n\r\n( :\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nWithin the editor:\r\n\r\n:iab  \\copyright  <ctrl-v>u00a9\r\n( that last token autoconverts to the copyright-symbol: © )\r\n\r\nwhen one taps Enter, then one gets the\r\ninvalid argument\r\nerror.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nWithin .vimrc\r\n\r\nset encoding=utf-8\r\nset fileencoding=utf-8\r\nscriptencoding utf-8\r\n\r\niab \\copyright ©\r\n( obviously from the same <ctrl-v>u00a9 key-sequence )\r\n\r\n:wq\r\n\r\nre-open your .vimrc, & neovim will balk with the\r\nE474 invalid argument\r\nerror, again.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nWe should be able to create iabbreviations with ANY unicode-character.\n\n### Neovim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.9.5 Build type: Release, LuaJIT 2.1.1703358377\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nyes Vim does the same damn bug, 9.1\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nUbuntu server, aarch64, 24.04LTS\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nbash 5.2.21\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nUbuntu's apt facility",
